<br>
       Most of the world runs on that BS.  That our internal system does not doesn't mean we allow everyone else the luxury.  It would be nice if they did allow inspectors free access to their country... but that has yet to happen.<br>
 <br>
<br>
&quot;By they way, the &quot;material breeches&quot; so far have been 12 empty warheads that could be used to transport chemical or bio weapons. They were purchased pre-gulf war (198 and never used. Did Iraq claim these on their documents? No. Should we go to war over that? It's Bush's call, but i'd say no.&quot;<br>
<br>
        So they fact they obviously lied in their declarations and statements is not reason to doubt them or enforce anything?  Mind you not only did we find these, we found them after giving advance notice we were going to be there, while escorted by Iraqi chaperones.  Imagine how likely it is we'd find more if we actually could do a surprise inspection?<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The first on is my favorite, she calls the 12,200 page document a plagorized copy of something. How the F*** does one plagorize their own work? LOL -- pack of lies? maybe, but plagorizm? pfft!&quot;<br>
<br>
      If I write a paper, and it happens to match word for word a paper I read by you... It can't be plagarism.  How can I plagarize my own paper?  pffft!   Much of what  Iraq did on the declaration was cut and paste what they are supposed to say from the mandate they were given and added &quot;we have no&quot;, &quot;no plans to create&quot;.... and so on.  It obviously doesn't match what the inspectors, even limited by the conditions of the searches, are finding.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm overloaded by the amount of unfactualized rhetoric in the media. Maybe i'm taking some of it out on ya'll -- maybe you're just as bored as me at work so you read my blabberings. Who knows. I've really started to feel that we should have just taken care of this asshole in the first place (first gulf war.)&quot;<br>
<br>
   Rhetoric goes both ways.  Anyone on either side of this argument without reservations needs their heads checked.   We *definitely* should have taken care of him in the first place.  Much of the anti-american sentiment is a result of how we ended the Gulf War.  A lot of Iraq that would have welcomed us as heros 10 years ago see us as unreliable at best, and traitors at worst as Bush Sr. put a lot of propaganda into an internal coup but provided 0 support once we got Iraq out of kuwait.   Instead of helping the Iraqi people as we did the Kuwaiti, we left them with Saddam and crippling sanctions that never cost Saddam a meal but did a lot of damage to the people of Iraq.<br>
<br>
    While I certainly have my general criticizms of GWB,  in this case I think he's doing as good a job as anyone could (well, except when he's making speeches).  If anything I have a lot of respect that he's sticking to this halfway through his first term.   It's a huge risk politically....   and it's really a lose-lose situation.   We go to war and take out Saddam, it's a bit hollow... I mean, if we were to wait for Saddam to gas/bomb us or a neighbor first then Bush could be the big hero stopping the evil dictator..... much like 9-11.... but *especially* after that disaster, he's simply not willing to have happen again.  So instead, we have an attempt at a preventative action... which understandably is going to be met with a lot of criticism.<br>
<br>
   The old concept of &quot;the good guys&quot; only going to war when the war is brought to them is harder to live by with the weapons used today.<br>
